<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900606-0095</DOCNO><DOCID>900606-0095.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Nevada Power Co.:   Contract with SCEcorp Unit   Is Rejected by Regulators</HL><DATE>06/06/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   SCE NVP</CO><LP>   Nevada's utility regulators rejected a power purchasecontract between Nevada Power Co. and SCEcorp's MissionEnergy Co. unit, citing &quot;unreasonably high costs for theproject.&quot;   &quot;The evidence showed that Nevada Power can get a betterdeal for ratepayers,&quot; said Tom Stephens, chairman of theNevada Public Service Commission. &quot;There is a clear need toadjust the price of this contract.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Under the proposed contract, Nevada Power would purchaseelectricity generated by a new 210-megawatt power plant thatMission would build on property adjacent to a Nevada Powerstation in the east Las Vegas valley. Nevada Power estimatesthe plant would cost about $88 million to build, and it hasagreed to buy the electricity for $6.16 per kilowatt permonth.   The commission has given Nevada Power 30 days to eithernegotiate a contract price that would be similar to what itwould cost if Nevada Power built the project itself, ordevelop an alternative.   Nevada Power plans to renegotiate with Mission, aspokeswoman said. Officials of SCEcorp, a Rosemead,Calif.-based utility holding company, weren't available forcomment.</TEXT></DOC>